{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = | name = Clara Tice | honorific_suffix = | image = ClaraTice1916.tif | image_size = | alt = Clara Tice and her dog, from a 1916 publication. | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1888|05|22}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|02|02|1888|05|22}} | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = American | education = | alma_mater = | known_for = Representative of bohemian Greenwich Village, known as "The Queen of Greenwich Village" | notable_works = ABC Dogs | style = | movement = Avant-garde | spouse = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = Robert Henri | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }}
'''Clara Tice''' (22 May 1888 – 2 February 1973) was an American [[avant-garde]] illustrator and artist, who spent most of her life in [[New York City, United States]]. Because of her provocative art and public appearances, she was seen as representative of bohemian [[Greenwich Village]] and thus known as "The Queen of Greenwich Village."<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=414–441|author=Keller, Marie T.|authorlink=Clara Tice|editor=Naomi Sawelson-Gorse}}</ref>
== Early life == According to herself and the ''[[New York Times]]'', in 1908 Tice was the first woman in Greenwich Village to bob her hair.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Vogue of Bobbed Hair: Of Course Greenwich Village Lassies Wear Short Locks, But Society's Doing It Too|journal=New York Times|date=27 June 1920|page=71}}</ref> Around the same time, Tice was able to study under the famous artist and teacher [[Robert Henri]]. In 1910, Henri and some of his artist friends, organized the first exhibition of Independent Artist. This art show, which was with its jury-free and no-awards concept quite a revolution at that time and thus received enormous attention, was financially backed by Tice and featured her works.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=415–416|author=Keller, Marie T.}}</ref>
== Immersion in the arts == A few years later, namely in 1915, Tice's fame skyrocketed when [[Anthony Comstock]], main founder of the [[Society for the Suppression of Vice]], tried to confiscate Tice's art at the well-known bohemian restaurant Polly's.<ref>{{cite book|last=Naumann|first=Francis M.|title=New York Dada 1915-23.|year=1994|publisher=Abrams|location=New York|page=117}}</ref> Thereafter images of Tice's artworks and photos of the artist were featured in magazines such as ''[[Vanity Fair (American magazine 1913–1936)|Vanity Fair]], Rogue, [[The Blind Man]],'' and ''[[Cartoons magazine]]''. During that time she had several one-person exhibitions and also worked on numerous other projects, for example, she created posters for bohemian costume balls and played herself in the 1922 version of the ''Greenwich Village Follies''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=416–429|author=Keller, Marie T.}}</ref>
During those years, Tice not only played an important part in Greenwich Village's colorful art scene, but also joined the Arensberg Circle in their uptown location. It was probably [[Marcel Duchamp]] who introduced Tice to Walter and Louise Arensberg and their salon. There she met [[Henri-Pierre Roché]], with whom she spent several evenings. Tice also participated in two projects by the Arensberg Circle: first, two of her works were shown in the first exhibition of the [[Society of Independent Artists]] and second, one of her works was featured in ''The Blind Man''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=425–427|author=Keller, Marie T.}}</ref>
During the 1920s, she illustrated about a dozen books with her erotic images,<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=432–434|author=Keller, Marie T.}}</ref> these are nowadays expensive collector's items. In 1940, her own book called ''ABC Dogs'' was published. It is a children's book in which each letter of the alphabet is represented by a dog breed whose name starts with the same letter.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tice|first=Clara|title=ABC Dogs|year=1940|publisher=Funk|location=New York}}</ref> This publication sparked renewed interest in Tice and her art. She also worked on her memoirs, which she never completed.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women in Dada: Essays on Sex, Gender, and Identity|year=1998|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=414–441|author=Keller, Marie T.}}</ref>
